    "body": "Thanks @jrainville @mprakhov :)\r\n\r\nJust to look at this from the angle of trying to make things as simple for the user (owner) as possible, I wonder what benefit there is for the new owner being able to differentiate between members who have auto-rejoined and those that have not yet? \r\n\r\nI know that sounds a bit crazy but just thinking that if the process of rejoining is so automated (assuming permissions have not been changed), that means that whether the user has rejoined the community or not is simply a product of them being online or offline after the new control node has come online, is that correct? And if permissions have changed, they would be kicked and not appear in the members list anyway.\r\n\r\nI'm just trying to think of the specific advantage to the owner of being able to differentiate between those members that have rejoined and those that haven't yet given it seems to be so automated and simply be a product of their online/offline status. \r\n\r\nIf we do want to amend the UI to flag which of the members are yet to re-share their addresses and rejoin we could do something minimal like the below but I think this is only needed if we can identify the core use case for the owner differentiating between the \"ghost\" members and those that have rejoined. Off the top of my head, I suppose it would be useful to know how many of my community I will actually reach with `@everyone` type messages etc?\r\n\r\n<img width=\"1440\" alt=\"Members\" src=\"https://github.com/status-im/status-desktop/assets/110033914/3ed8d5ad-e5e3-40c2-a911-52e48cb9d182\">\r\n",
